<font color="#FF0000">THE EVENT &amp; QUESTIONS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Apr 28 16:16:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Boy, a lot of questions came to mind as I read Doc Spatz's post on the trip to &quot;Little Saigon&quot; and they include what was the event celebrating, just the arrival of the traveling wall, or was the wall just part of the Air show or was the air show and the traveling wall just a part of a commemeration Of the Fall of Saigon or did this date go unnotice to the organizers and who were the organizers, a group from the Vietnamese community or was everything arrange and organized by veterans organizations or by the city?  I may be off the cuff here, but wouldn't the nature of the event and who was involved play a part of how the different groups responded to, let's say, the displaying of the wall.<br><br>
This would be a good example as, if I was a son of a Vietnamese veteran, or that veteran himself, or a family member who lost someone in the war, would I not ponder while looking at that list of american dead, where is our wall, where is our dead names? Not to mention the names of civilians.<br><br>
Dr. Spatz's reference of that pilot and his feeling about returning to Vietnam, is so reminisent of the Cuban-Americans plight after Castros gain of control of the government and the fiasco of the Bay of Pigs. To this day, the word is that many would return to Cuba if things were to change once Castro dies, but with the passage of time, who really believes that the majority of Cuban-Americans would return?  Much of this sentiment stems from the fact that, for most in this country, they have family left in the &quot;old country&quot;. Also, the fact for both groups, that they left Vietnam and Cuba under circumstances different from those that left Italy, France, England, Germany and the like. These two groups left with &quot;guns to their heads&quot;, in that the choice of staying for many were unpleasent if not deadly.<br><br>
Anyone have more info on this event?
